present, and envision the future. In this book, Reyhan Durmaz uses these stories to demonstrate and analyze the mutually constitutive relationship between these two religions in the Middle Ages. With an in-depth study of storytelling in late antiquity and the mechanisms of hagiographical transmission between Christianity and Islam in the Middle Ages, Durmaz develops a nuanced understanding of saints’ stories as a tool for building identity, memory, and authority across confessional boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChristian saintsxHistoryyTo 1500vComparative studies. 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslamxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMuslim saintsxHistoryyTo 1500vComparative studies. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520386471?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520386471423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520386471/original  a978-3-11-076649-3  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY